Gmail Factory — Hermes-Cloak vendor build
=========================================

This directory contains a slimmed and adapted fork of:

    https://github.com/ShadowHackrs/Gmail-infinity
    (c) 2026 Shadow / ShadowHackrs, all rights reserved

The upstream project is shipped under a proprietary licence. We retain
attribution here and have NOT modified the upstream copyright notices
that survive inside individual source files. This vendor build exists
solely to allow Hermes — a personal automation framework — to call the
Gmail account-creation engine through the same Cloak-managed browser
infrastructure that powers the rest of the toolkit.

Modifications applied in this build
-----------------------------------

1. Removed the interactive TUI (auto_gmail_creator.py) and replaced it
   with a non-interactive ``hermes_runner.py`` CLI driven over stdin
   JSON.

2. Removed the Selenium engine (``core/selenium_runner.py``), the
   Appium / Android engine (``core/android_creator.py``), the free-proxy
   scraper (``core/proxy_fetcher.py``) and the voice OTP server
   (``services/voice.py``). The Hermes integration only uses the
   Playwright path.

3. Replaced ``core/behavior.py`` (numpy + scipy Bezier math) with a
   pure-Python pydoll-derived implementation so this vendor does not
   need numpy or scipy.

4. Baked Cloak CDP integration into ``core/stealth_browser.py``: when
   ``BROWSER_CDP_URL`` is set we ``connect_over_cdp`` to the Cloak
   Manager's CDP proxy and skip every local fingerprint spoof. When
   ``BROWSER_CDP_URL`` is unset the original launch path runs unchanged.

5. Trimmed ``core/ui.py`` to just the logging helpers used by other
   modules. The TUI screens are gone.

6. Replaced ``data/accounts.json`` with an empty array and
   ``config/proxies.txt`` with an empty template (upstream shipped
   sample data tied to the original author).

No upstream functionality has been added to the public Hermes plug-in
itself. The vendor lives in its own /usr/local/lib/gmail-factory venv,
isolated from Hermes' own dependencies.

If you are the upstream author and want this code removed or the
attribution improved, please open an issue on the
xaroundx/Hermes-Cloak-Patch repository.
